**Sec. 70401 – Enhancement of Employer-Provided Child Care Credit**  
The bill raises the employer-provided child care credit rate from 25 % to 40 % (50 % for eligible small businesses) and doubles the maximum credit to $500,000 ($600,000 for eligible small businesses). It also expands the definition of “eligible small business” to use a 5-year gross-receipts test instead of 3 years and allows third-party intermediaries to claim the credit. The changes apply to amounts paid or incurred after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70402 – Enhancement of Adoption Credit**  
The bill makes the $5,000 adoption credit refundable and subjects it to the regular tax rules. It also indexes the credit amounts for inflation starting in 2025, using 2001 as the base year. The refundable portion is no longer subject to the carryforward rules that apply to non-refundable credits. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70403 – Recognizing Indian Tribal Governments for Adoption Credit**  
The bill explicitly includes Indian tribal governments as eligible entities that can certify whether a child has special needs for adoption credit purposes, aligning them with state and local governments. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70404 – Enhancement of Dependent Care Assistance Program**  
The bill raises the maximum dependent care assistance program exclusion from $5,000 to $7,500 ($3,750 for married filing separately) and applies the increase to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70405 – Enhancement of Child and Dependent Care Tax Credit**  
The bill increases the applicable percentage from 30 % to 50 % for taxpayers with adjusted gross income up to $15,000, reduces it by 1 percentage point for every $2,000 (or $4,000 on a joint return) of AGI above $15,000, and sets a floor of 20 % for all taxpayers. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70411 – Tax Credit for Contributions to Scholarship Granting Organizations**  
The bill creates a new $1,700 non-refundable individual tax credit for contributions to state-certified scholarship granting organizations (SGOs). Contributions are limited to $1,700 per taxpayer per year and are not deductible as charitable contributions. The credit is reduced by any state tax credit claimed for the same contributions. SGOs must award scholarships to at least 10 students, spend at least 90 % of income on scholarships, and meet other eligibility requirements. The credit applies to taxable years ending after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70412 – Exclusion for Employer Payments of Student Loans**  
The bill permanently extends the exclusion from gross income for employer payments of student loans, removing the previous expiration date of January 1, 2026. The $5,250 annual exclusion is indexed for inflation starting in 2026. This change applies to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70413 – Additional Expenses Treated as Qualified Higher Education Expenses for 529 Accounts**  
The bill expands the definition of “qualified higher education expenses” to include elementary and secondary school tuition, curriculum materials, books, online educational materials, tutoring, standardized test fees, dual enrollment costs, and educational therapies for students with disabilities. It also doubles the lifetime limit for 529 account rollovers from $10,000 to $20,000. These changes apply to distributions made after the date of enactment and to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70414 – Certain Postsecondary Credentialing Expenses Treated as Qualified Higher Education Expenses for 529 Accounts**  
The bill creates a new category of “qualified postsecondary credentialing expenses” under 529 plans, including tuition, fees, books, supplies, equipment, testing fees, and continuing education required to obtain or maintain recognized postsecondary credentials. Recognized credentials include industry-recognized certificates, apprenticeships, licenses, and other credentials identified by the Secretary of Labor. These changes apply to distributions made after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70415 – Modification of Excise Tax on Investment Income of Certain Private Colleges and Universities**  
The bill revises the excise tax on net investment income of private colleges and universities by adjusting the applicable tax rates to 1.4 %, 4 %, and 8 % based on the institution’s student-adjusted endowment. It expands the definition of “applicable educational institution” to include any college or university with at least 3,000 tuition-paying students, more than 50 % of whom are U.S. residents, and with a student-adjusted endowment of at least $500,000. It also requires such institutions to report the number of tuition-paying students on their tax returns. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70416 – Expanding Application of Tax on Excess Compensation Within Tax-Exempt Organizations**  
The bill removes the expiration date for the excise tax on excess compensation paid by tax-exempt organizations, making the $1 million cap permanent. The change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70421 – Permanent Renewal and Enhancement of Opportunity Zones**  
The bill makes Opportunity Zone designations permanent by establishing a decennial (10-year) renewal process starting July 1, 2026, and every 10 years thereafter. It removes the special rule for Puerto Rico, applies the designation cap to all states equally, and extends the holding period for qualified opportunity zone property to 10 years for a full basis step-up. These changes apply to areas designated after the date of enactment and to Puerto Rico on December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70422 – Permanent Enhancement of Low-Income Housing Tax Credit**  
The bill permanently increases the state housing credit ceiling for the low-income housing tax credit to 12 % of qualified investment per year and repeals the temporary 1.125 % rate. It also modifies the tax-exempt bond financing requirement, allowing a 25 % basis allocation if at least 5 % of the building’s basis is financed with tax-exempt bonds issued after December 31, 2025. These changes apply to buildings placed in service in taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70423 – Permanent Extension of New Markets Tax Credit**  
The bill makes the New Markets Tax Credit permanent by removing the expiration date of December 31, 2025. It also allows unused limitations to be carried forward for up to five years and treats any unused limitation from before 2026 as occurring in 2025. These changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70424 – Permanent and Expanded Reinstatement of Partial Deduction for Charitable Contributions of Individuals Who Do Not Elect to Itemize**  
The bill increases the standard deduction charitable contribution allowance from $300 ($600 for joint filers) to $1,000 ($2,000 for joint filers) and makes it permanent. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70425 – 0.5 Percent Floor on Deduction of Contributions Made by Individuals**  
The bill imposes a 0.5 % of contribution base floor on charitable deductions for individuals, applying after the application of other subparagraphs (D, C, B, E, A, and G). It also allows disallowed contributions to be carried forward only in years where the floor is exceeded and modifies the 60 % cash contribution limit to coordinate with the new floor. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70426 – 1-Percent Floor on Deduction of Charitable Contributions Made by Corporations**  
The bill imposes a 1 % of taxable income floor on corporate charitable deductions, reducing the deduction allowance to the extent that contributions exceed 1 % of taxable income but do not exceed 10 %. It also revises the 5-year carryforward rules and allows disallowed contributions to be carried forward only in years where the 10 % limit is exceeded. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70427 – Permanent Increase in Limitation on Cover Over of Tax on Distilled Spirits**  
The bill permanently increases the cover over of the tax on distilled spirits from $12.50 to $13.25 per proof gallon, effective for spirits brought into the United States after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70428 – Nonprofit Community Development Activities in Remote Native Villages**  
The bill exempts from federal income tax the income derived by certain Alaska Native corporations from activities related to fisheries in the Bering Sea and Aleutian Islands, including harvesting, processing, and marketing. It also provides tax-free treatment for the transfer of related assets to these corporations within 18 months of enactment. These provisions remain in effect for the duration of the western Alaska community development quota program.

**Sec. 70429 – Adjustment of Charitable Deduction for Certain Expenses Incurred in Support of Native Alaskan Subsistence Whaling**  
The bill increases the deductible amount for qualified expenses incurred in support of Native Alaskan subsistence whaling from $10,000 to $50,000, applying to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70430 – Exception to Percentage of Completion Method of Accounting for Certain Residential Construction Contracts**  
The bill modifies the percentage of completion method of accounting to apply a 3-year lookback period for residential construction contracts (instead of 2 years) and expands the exception to include all residential construction contracts, not just “home construction contracts.” It also updates the reference to section 460(e)(4) in the alternative minimum tax rules. These changes apply to contracts entered into in taxable years beginning after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70431 – Expansion of Qualified Small Business Stock Gain Exclusion**  
The bill phases in the exclusion of gain from qualified small business stock (QSBS) over three to five years, with 50 % excluded after 3 years, 75 % after 4 years, and 100 % after 5 years. It also increases the per-issuer limitation to $15 million (indexed for inflation after 2026) and raises the aggregate gross assets limit to $75 million (indexed). These changes apply to taxable years beginning after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70432 – Repeal of Revision to De Minimis Rules for Third Party Network Transactions**  
The bill reinstates the pre-2021 de minimis exception for third-party settlement organizations, requiring reporting only if aggregate payments exceed $20,000 and 200 transactions. It also applies the de minimis rule to backup withholding, requiring reporting only if aggregate transactions exceed the reporting threshold. These changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70433 – Increase in Threshold for Requiring Information Reporting with Respect to Certain Payees**  
The bill raises the threshold for reporting payments to payees from $600 to $2,000 and indexes it for inflation after 2026. It also updates related reporting and backup withholding thresholds to match the new $2,000 threshold. These changes apply to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70434 – Treatment of Certain Qualified Sound Recording Productions**  
The bill expands the qualified production expenses (QPE) deduction to include qualified sound recording productions, with a $150,000 per-production limit. It also allows bonus depreciation for such productions and requires them to be placed in service at the time of initial release or broadcast. These changes apply to productions commencing in taxable years ending after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70435 – Exclusion of Interest on Loans Secured by Rural or Agricultural Real Property**  
The bill excludes 25 % of the interest income from qualified real estate loans secured by rural or agricultural property from gross income. It defines “qualified lender” to include banks, insurance companies, and certain federally chartered institutions, and defines “qualified real estate loan” to include loans secured by rural or agricultural real estate made after the date of enactment. These changes apply to taxable years ending after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70436 – Reduction of Transfer and Manufacturing Taxes for Certain Devices**  
The bill eliminates the federal excise tax on firearms that are not machineguns or destructive devices, reducing the tax rate to $0 for such firearms. It also updates cross-references to reflect the change. These changes apply to calendar quarters beginning more than 90 days after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70437 – Treatment of Capital Gains from the Sale of Certain Farmland Property**  
The bill creates a new section allowing taxpayers to elect installment reporting of gain from the sale of qualified farmland property to qualified farmers. The gain is recognized ratably over four years, with the first installment due on the tax return due date for the year of sale. The property must have been used as a farm for at least 10 years and subject to a covenant restricting its use as farmland. These changes apply to sales or exchanges in taxable years beginning after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70438 – Extension of Rules for Treatment of Certain Disaster-Related Personal Casualty Losses**  
The bill extends the special rules for disaster-related personal casualty losses under the Taxpayer Certainty and Disaster Tax Relief Act of 2020 by substituting the date of enactment for the original enactment date. This change applies retroactively.

**Sec. 70439 – Restoration of Taxable REIT Subsidiary Asset Test**  
The bill increases the asset test for a taxable REIT subsidiary (TRS) from 20 % to 25 % of the REIT’s total assets, effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025. [end of text]


